Premise: Socio-economic factors, cultural influences, and healthcare access can significantly impact the management of heart failure in African-American patients.

Reasoning: Considering the patient's well-to-do socio-economic condition, he may have access to a variety of food options that can either support or hinder his heart health. However, living in an unsafe neighborhood may limit his access to fresh, healthy foods. Additionally, as an older male African-American, he may have cultural dietary preferences that could affect his heart health.

Solution: Encourage the patient to focus on a heart-healthy diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and low-fat dairy products. Suggest meal planning and shopping at local markets or grocery stores that offer a variety of fresh produce. 

Anticipate Barrier: The patient may face challenges in finding affordable healthy food options in his unsafe neighborhood or may struggle to adjust to a new dietary routine due to cultural preferences.

Solve Barrier: Provide resources such as local food assistance programs, community gardens, or online grocery delivery services. Offer culturally appropriate recipes and meal ideas that align with his dietary preferences.

Educate: Educate the patient on the importance of nutrition in managing heart failure, explaining how a heart-healthy diet can improve his overall health and quality of life. Encourage him to make small, sustainable changes to his diet and involve his family or support system in meal planning and preparation.